abstract: The second-quarter corporate bond market bonanza that lifted Wall Street’s underwriting fortunes may have been a blip. Although bankers say plenty of deals are in the works, there may be reason to temper their enthusiasm, Breakingviews writes.
snippet: The second-quarter corporate bond market bonanza that lifted Wall Street’s underwriting fortunes may have been a blip. Although bankers say plenty of deals are in the works, there may be reason to temper their enthusiasm, Breakingviews writes.
lead_paragraph: The second-quarter corporate bond market bonanza that lifted Wall Street’s underwriting fortunes may have been a blip. At least that’s what two of its biggest beneficiaries, JPMorgan Chase and Moody’s, think. Although bankers say plenty of deals are in the works, there may be reason to temper their enthusiasm, Breakingviews writes.

headline.main: Could This Be the End of the Bond Blowout?
